  For sociolinguists in particular, one major point of interest in South Louisiana is the two major local identity categories: Creole and Cajun.
  As will be discussed in Sections \ref{sec:creole_identity} and \ref{sec:cajun_identity}, the definitions for these two categories each have rather winding histories.
  For \lexi{Creole}, the term has referred to various groups based on country of origin and/or skin color, ending up as a something of a synonym for Black for many people today, though the modern-day use of the term is certainly maintains some variability.
  For \lexi{Cajun}, what started as a term referring to the Acadian diaspora in Louisiana has morphed to refer to people from various backgrounds with the notable restriction that a Cajun and Black identities are mutually exclusive.
  These categories were initially born out of Louisiana's history as a French and Spanish colony before becoming part of the United States, and as such, maintain a regional uniqueness while also coming to be influenced by the racialized social system \parencite{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997} of the broader US.
  Indeed, the aim of the present study is to better understand if and in what ways Creole and Cajun identities have become racialized \parencite{omi_racial_1986}.
  
  Of more purely linguistic interest, language is a distinguishing feature of South Louisiana in that there is a history of Creoles and Cajuns speaking French and Creole (F\&C)\footnote{
    \lexi{F\&C} will be used as an umbrella term in this study for all French-related language varieties spoken in South Louisiana, as will be discussed further in Section \ref{sec:french_vs_creole}.
  }.
  Today, these languages are spoken in South Louisiana as heritage languages, whereas they were the dominant languages perhaps as recently as the mid 20th century.
  Indeed, by the 1980s, South Louisiana was still being described as ``un exemple par excellence d'une société multilingue''\footnote{
    An ideal example of a multilingual society.
  } \parencite[p.~16]{neumann_creole_1985}.
  F\&C in Louisiana are unique cultural resources that are generally valued by many among the populace and even exploited for commercial gain, but both are on the decline.
  Both languages have been documented as showing variation along geographic and social dimensions, as will be discussed in Section \ref{sec:reg_socio_variation}, though recent work focusing on ethnic and/or racial variation in and around the Lafayette area, the geographic focus of this study, is lacking.
  Furthermore, while sociological and anthropological work on race has begun to inform work in sociolinguistics since \textcite{rosa_unsettling_2017}, there remains ample room in the field for studying racialization.
  Combining this gap in the descriptive literature on F\&C with the need for more analyses of racialization from a sociolinguistic perspective, the objective of this dissertation is thus to examine how Creole and Cajun identities in Louisiana relate to race.
  Chapter \ref{chap:pronoun_variation} will analyse subject pronoun usage to establish whether these function as markers of Creole and Cajun identity.
  Chapter \ref{chap:personal_networks} will look at the personal social networks of participants to understand whether there is segregation, homophily, and along what lines.
  Finally, Chapter \ref{chap:ethnic_race_meaning} will examine how participants spoke about their identities in terms of race and ethnicity.

  \section{Race and ethnicity}
    \label{sec:race_ethnicity}
    As Decker (1994) suggested, when using race in sociological research, it is important to explicitly define \lexi{race} in order to make clear how it is being used \parencite[as cited in][p.~22]{omi_racial_1997}.
    This is especially true in the present study where the goal is to understand if \lexi{Creole} and \lexi{Cajun} are ethnic categories or racialized categories.
    The following is thus not only an explanation of how the concept of race will be used throughout this dissertation but also how it contrasts with ethnicity.

    Early conceptualizations of race and ethnicity in the social sciences were relatively straight forward but often problematic, as well, especially in the case of race.
    Indeed, early attempts at outlining taxonomies of race, such as \citeauthor{blumenbach_natural_1865}'s (\citeyear{blumenbach_natural_1865}), were inherently racist, and unsurprisingly, always placed Whites/Europeans at the top of the hierarchy \parencite[Eze, 1997, as cited in][p.~654]{hesse_racialized_2007}.
    Later definitions did not give race a much better treatment, even when provided by prominent sociologists.
    \textcite{weber_economy_1978}, for instance, defined race as ``common inherited and inheritable traits that actually derive from common descent'' arising when a ``common trait'' is highlighted due to an antagonistic relationship with those having an ``obviously different'' trait (p.~385).
    While this definition incorporates the idea of conflict, which is readily apparent in modern views of race, it remains essentialist in nature.

    On the other hand, early definitions of ethnicity were not particularly problematic for espousing harmful views -- intentionally or not -- but were instead inconsistent.
    For instance, while \textcite{weber_economy_1978} defined ethnic groups as ``groups that entertain subjective belief in their common descent because of similarities of physical type or of customs or both, or because of memories of colonization and migration'' (389), Huxley \& Haddon (1935) used the term as a substitute for race to identify groups at the national level \parencite[as cited in][pp.~481-482]{banton_ethnic_2000}, and a bit later \textcite{gans_symbolic_1979} implicitly defined ethnic groups in terms of immigration, giving Jewish people, Catholics, and Italians as examples in the US.
    Perhaps the most general of these earlier definitions was that proposed by Moerman (1965) first in his work on the Lue in Thailand \parencite{eriksen_ethnicity_2010} and later echoed by others (\foreign{e.g.}, \citeauthor[Giles, 1979, as cited in][]{le_page_acts_1985}, \citeyear[p.~2]{le_page_acts_1985}; \citeauthor{le_page_acts_1985}, \citeyear[p.~2]{le_page_acts_1985}), was that an ethnic group is those individuals who perceive themselves as belonging to the same ethnic category.
    Portions of these definitions of ethnicity are still found in modern definitions, though in the case of Weber's, the involvement of colonization has become central to definitons of race rather than ethnicity.

    These definitions of ethnicity also suggest that there has always been some indecision over whether to treat race and ethnicity as separate analytical concepts or not, and by the 2000s, some had maintained a a distinction between them while others had not or had at least treated it as a blurry distinction \parencite[p.~25]{brubaker_ethnicity_2009}.
    \textcite{loveman_is_1999}, for instance, who proposed abandoning the distinction, argued that the distinction between race and ethnicity is born out of the context of the US and so not generalizable (p.~891), while \textcite{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997} argued instead that the distinction is important, stating that  ``[e]thnicity has a primarily sociocultural foundation, and ethnic groups have exhibited tremendous malleability in terms of who belongs,'' whereas races are ``initially ... imposed externally to justify the collective exploitation of a people and are maintained to preserve status differences'' (469).
    He thus later pointed to colonialism as the origin of race and the formation of nation-states as the origin of ethnicity \parencite[pp.902-903]{bonilla-silva_essential_1999}, colonialism naturally not being relegated to the US.
    Indeed, \textcite{rosa_unsettling_2017} implicitly agreed when they suggested that studies of race should not be relegated to just the US since European colonialism did not occur exclusively in the US (pp.~634-635).
    It is perhaps because of influential work on race of people like Bonilla-Silva that \textcite{eriksen_ethnicity_2010}, working on ethnicity, revised his earlier view from conceptualizing race and ethnicity as equivalent to treating them as distinct (p.~8).

    For both race and ethnicity, a common thread in their conceptualizations is the idea of contact between groups.
    Indeed, in the case of ethnicity, \textcite{eriksen_ethnicity_2010} argued that a group sees itself as an ethnic group only when there is contact with other such groups and those groups see each other as different despite similarities or differences in their respective cultures (p.~16)
    This is thought of as making such identities salient where they once were not, which is perhaps the reason that the origin of ethnicities lies in the late 18th century with ``European processes of transition from sovereign states into nation-states and to immigration of 'nationals' to foreign lands'' \parencite[A. D. Smith, 1986, as cited in][p.~903]{bonilla-silva_essential_1999}.
    This results in modern definitions such as an ethnic group being any ``named human populations with shared ancestry myths, histories and cultures, having an association with a specific territory and a sense of solidarity'' \parencite[p.~27]{guibernau_ethnic_1997}, the implication being that those histories and ideas of territory become more important to people when they are more at risk of losing them after immigrating.
    This would also be true of similar though more cognitive definitions of ethnicity such as ``a social and cognitive structure that leads people to recognize themselves and/or be recognized by others as having real or putative common ancestry, shared culture, and/or a shared historical past'' \parencite[Brubaker et al., 2004; Cronell \& Hartmann, 1998, as cited in][p.~41]{roth_conceptualizations_2023}.
    What one ends up with is the idea that ethnicity is about belief in a shared history of some sort that is brought to the forefront through contact with others.

