    In the case of race, not only is contact involved in modern definitions but also conflict.
    \textcite{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997}, for instance, defined a race as a population that is the effect of ``practices of opposition'' between it and another population ``at the economic, political, social, and ideological levels,'' which is ``usually, although not always,'' tied to concepts of the human body \foreign{post hoc} (p.~472).
    Although some still give the body as the primary trait that racial categories are attached to \parencite[\foreign{e.g.}][pp.~6-7]{susberry_racial_2004}, the key aspect of the above definition is that this association is only made after a group has already been labeled as a race to justify actions against said group.
    Groups that have been racialized can be marked by appearance but also by language, religion, or culture, as well \parencite[pp.~636-637]{grosfoguel_racism_2015}.
    Examples of racialized peoples thus include Jewish people in Europe, the Irish in England, and American Indians in the US \parencite[p.~472]{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997}.
    This is why \textcite{grosfoguel_race_2004} warned that too much focus on color categories obscures ``other forms of racialization'' (p.~326), and \textcite{rosa_unsettling_2017}, speaking of both race and language, argued that studies of these subjects should not begin with ``racialized bodies and communicative practices'' as this limits one's ability to see how these categories ``become racially and linguistically legible,'' meaning that analyses must start with historical and institutional contexts instead (p.~637).
    
