    The historical context for race is colonialism.
    As \textcite{hesse_racialized_2007} argued, race is not about bodies but rather about Europeanness vs non-Europeanness (p.~646), which led him to propose the idea of racialized modernity as he viewed modernity as going hand in hand with the development of the concept of Europe versus non-Europe that became symbolized as race.
    Likewise, the naturalization of languages with races was also part of this \parencite[p.~623]{rosa_unsettling_2017}.
    While Hesse's focus was more generally on modernity, colonialism was a major component of this process as it brought about the possibility of enrichment through the exploitation of Others.
    Indeed, \textcite{grosfoguel_race_2004} similarly stated that Europeans and non-Europeans were the two groups involved in the ``global racial/ethnic hierarchy'' and that this hierarchy stems from the capitalist world economy (p.~320).

    Without the presence of resources that one population wishes to monopolize, as with colonialism, there is little in the way of motivation for any form of rational racism.
    This is why \textcite{ray_theory_2019} defined race as ``a relationship between persons'' constructed through ``the distribution of social, psychological, and material resources'' (p.~29).
    It is through the desire to control the distribution of resources that racial schema are activated and then attached to those resources \parencite[p.~32]{ray_theory_2019}.
    For example, only because access to education exists is the access to that education partitioned along racialized lines in order to help one population maintain its privileged position with respect to this resource.
    Once racialized, race becomes a form of capital where the dominant, unmarked population wields more power.
    In the case of the US then, Whiteness has been described as a form of property ``encompassing `all of a person's legal rights''' \parencite[Harris, 1995, as cited in][p.~30]{ray_theory_2019}.
